== Dharma talk on the untainted wisdom of the view

...remind everybody of the Dzogchen view, which has been considered too simple: so simple that it's beyond capture. So simple that it's actually, as Niguma states it (an 11th-century Yogini), a fault: people will ignore the view because it's too simple. 

It's this very awareness that you're hearing me with.

Just this. #btw[Dawai rests with the sangha in pure presence].

And the ancient yogis termed it gzhi, the basis, because it's able to contain, so to speak, any experience that you have. And this is what the yogi can validate and verify, and then utilize the validation as evidence: yes, awareness is here as I'm thinking. It's here; it knows that I'm feeling. There's a knowingness that I'm feeling something.

So awareness is like a mountain in that sense: it's not going anywhere. And all the experiences, you can just leave them alone; like the ocean is just moving within space. Space is steady and stable, able to contain the ocean.

So they call it the basis; and the basis has to be empty of substantiality. It cannot have a reference point or any kind of anchor into substantial referentiality, like an island of its own. It has to be empty of existence so it can hold all of our love and hate, and ups and downs, and neutrals.

But every Buddha, every realized yogi that you've ever heard of, has reorientated into this part of their mind. The reorientation into this pure aspect of your mind cannot be fabricated, otherwise we'd have huge fallacies in the Dharma. It cannot be created. It cannot be willed into place. The only thing you can do is let these preoccupations come off of you. Let the searching come off of you. Let the trying to purify, or trying to be enlightened, trying to reach some destination: let that come off of you.

The holding of past pain, and you know, which is just current pain. Character sheets of our identity fabrications---who we are, who we think we are, who others think we are---they hang on us, don't they? But awareness, or the nature of mind, Svabhavana, Rangzhen, Rigpa, is untainted by any story that you could tell about Rigpa.

So this is a very special part of our minds here, isn't it? It has always held us, just like the mind of the dreamer has always held the dream. But a dream cannot harm the cognizance. Just like that, your experiences cannot harm Rigpa.

And so maybe it's like a cake: we have layers of doing and holding. In the coarse layers we may be thinking, "Oh, what do I got to do later? I'm thinking about that and planning that and everything." So I'm sort of displacing myself into the future, out of pure presence.

On the inner mind---in the heart I may be feeling remorseful; I may be feeling sad about the world, the state of the world, or something like that. So I have this disposition, and it's layered. I could have this... maybe I woke up this morning and I thought, "The world is such a sad place," but then I talked to a friend and they said, "Oh, I cannot sell you that car," or whatever, and then you get sad. See how it's layered? You get sad on top of the sad about the world.

And then somebody in the group asks you, "Hey, how you doing today?" "Well, I'm sad." "I got some good news for you, I just got a new guitar." "No, that's sad, because I don't have a guitar." You see, so it ends up tainting everything---this predisposition, the preprogramming.

But when we do effortless abiding, when you just leave it be---leave awareness be, leave the meditation be, leave your conduct be, and any fruition, leave that be too—then what's happening is the programming is burning out. Any predisposition conditioning that you've been intoxicated with; and trust me, I know growing up in this collective, kids go through it, man. The mind goes through it.

So chances are you've been hurt, or you've been intoxicated by confusion in some way or something like that—disempowered. And so whatever that is, you can let it come off of you. The tension---you can allow it, free it up to come out of you: out of your chest, out of your stomach, out of your pelvis.

So it's very nuanced, everybody, this is Madhyamaka, the middle way; you can let your conduct be. If you're going to wash the dishes, or you're petting the doggy or something, just let that be. That's the little healthy paradox that you can actually let be while you're doing. Only if you've discovered awareness, the basis of your mind, because now you can reside in the basis, and everything else is naturally just let be within the view.

So that's why they call it the basis okay everybody, and why this particular approach hinges on that. So if somebody asks me for pointing out, for example, I just look at them and allow that clear light awareness. And then they see, because they know that that is the very intimate, most precious part of their own mind. So they say, "Oh yes, of course," they recognize that---that's home. I live there.

This is your birthless right to access this part of your mind. To come home. It is your right, you are entitled to that. All you have to do is want to be free, one little bit.

So any questions so far, comments, anything about this stuff? Making sense, yeah? Good.

Yeah, that's a great question there. #btw[Dawai reads the chat]. How can we let be in the course of action?" I believe is what I saw pop up there. Let's make sure. "How can one let be while still acting?

Yes so if you're in the whirlpool, for example, if you're in the ocean and there's a whirlpool, and you're stuck in it, you're going to be circulating around in the whirlpool. But if you go underwater and you dive and you go outside of the whirlpool, now you can see the whirlpool, but you're no longer in it. That's how awareness works.

So at first, when you get pointed to awareness, this varies from person to person. Some people immediately take refuge, like somebody who's grabbing a life preserver or something like that in the ocean, right? One of those little donuts that they throw. Somebody grabs awareness and says, "Yes, this is it." They've been looking for it, they've been reading about it, they've been hearing about it, and now they're realizing it.

Other people have conceptual dispositions, so it's a little bit more tricky. You may see it and then immediately apprehend it or create a story about it. But somehow you gotta get out of the whirlpool.

Typically, when you get pointed out in Dzogchen, it's like somebody took you... there's this whirlpool, and somebody took you out for a second, and then you got back in. Because then you say, "oh, I saw this awareness, this is awesome" but no, you're really just in a whirlpool again, making stories about the awareness. Now others, for example, if you follow the traditional route of doing 500,000 recitations of mantra and 100,000 prostrations, Shedra, Khordé Rushen preliminaries, Tsalung preliminaries, and all this stuff, if you do all that, then maybe when somebody pulls you out, you may be there a little bit longer in the lake rather than in the whirlpool.

But we are habituated, we have programmed ourselves through plasticity, ingrained complex, multi‑layered plasticity. We have programmed... were under the sway of kind of intoxication. And so that's karmic momentum, that's inertia, essentially, if you really recognize the view, it'd be more like inertia than. So you have to allow for that karmic momentum, just like a train passing by---let that train pass by. And if you hop on a train, well, you go for a ride, you know. In awareness, it's okay either way. You get to the point where you can say, no, I'm going to let this train pass by. And then maybe the train only has two carts, a very short train this time.

So that's what your triggers are. Every time you hear something in the media or some family member says something to you, it can be a train. Now are you jumping on that train, or no? Only an awareness holder has that choice, that's true free will in my opinion. You can say, no, I'm not boarding this train. Too many people on it, wrong destination. That's freedom. So the train of wanting a cigarette, the train of wanting sex, all these trains, which all become better trains when you're not addicted to them. Ironically.

So you have to, in my opinion, in this approach, true effortlessness, although it's endorsed out there in the contemplative and spiritual worlds---true effortlessness cannot be possible without the recognition of the basis of your mind, the base cognition, the nature of mind. It cannot be possible. How could you ever do effortlessness unless you orientated yourself into the actual container for experience? It's very, very logical.

That's like the planet relocating itself into space. So the planet's still there, no problem, but you're no longer spinning around having earthquakes and volcanoes and stuff, you know, now you're the space. And the more you let be at first, we are habituated so strongly into the planet, to be the planet. So just like, you can verify this scientifically even when you go to sleep and you dream, look how much you're in that dream, you think it's real, you're convinced.

Now a yogi, a long‑time awareness practitioner, someone who's in effortlessness, that dream will be just like sitting here having thoughts. That dream will not even captivate you at all. You won't be shaking your leg like the doggies when you're dreaming, or growling at nobody. Don't we do that? We go to war with nobody, our own mind.

So anyway, that's a strong, almost dogmatic response there [addressing the Sangha who asked the question] but I believe you have to recognize the nature of mind in order for true effortlessness. And I've actually called it pure effortlessness, when you're around phase three. You know we have four phases in our approach---you get introduced to this part of your mind, you familiarize with it, and then you can go into pure effortlessness.

But how can the planet truly just be free of itself unless it's truly in space? It has to be truly in space for it to rotate and do whatever it wants by itself. But that reorientation, that's going to depend on the person, different people warm up to the view in different ways.

But there's a great alleviation, there's a great relief happening once you start to come into your fullness, into your wholeness. Because all that smallness, all that congesting into the body or congesting into this being behind the eyes, and thinking that you're just in the brain---all that contraction---now you have space to let that contraction breathe out.

And there's also revelation, by the way, non‑dual revelation with your environment. Remember, the five aggregates include form. The four foundations of mindfulness include the environment. This is our body---the environment, so we're letting that be too as one mind. And as Longchenpa says, "mind resolves itself within phenomena," because we're hooked into phenomena, we reify phenomena, and that's the whole reason for our confusion, for our smallness.

Longchenpa says, "mind resolves itself within phenomena" as those hooks, those _shenpa_ hooks, come off and come out. But then "phenomena also resolve themselves within mind," he says. So now you're starting to see, or luminosity is realized, even the body is realized as luminosity. And you may encounter this point where you almost see the form and the luminosity at the same time.

Somebody had described that recently in an email to me. It was wonderful how they described it, I should ask them if I could share it. But they described form and emptiness, emptiness and form, in terms of luminosity, perfectly. And it wasn't this clean‑cut nomenclature, technical vocabulary, all this stuff. It was just this really personalized account; real peer‑reviewed stuff. By the way, if you're in here and you're okay with me sharing that, I think it's such a great sharing that it could benefit others.

So when we integrate with Tögal practices, we basically say, okay, you know, we pull these rays and we see the bindus and we do clear light practices and things like that, mostly just clear light awareness. Then the environment really starts to come into our practice just as much as thoughts and emotions.


